## **Why This Hierarchical Framing Is Correct**\
\
### **1. It Prevents Mode Proliferation**\
\
If you treat all three as "equal choices," you get:\
- 
\f2 \uc0\u10060 
\f0  Analysis paralysis ("which one should I use?")\
- 
\f2 \uc0\u10060 
\f0  Inconsistent output quality (wrong mode for wrong audience)\
- 
\f2 \uc0\u10060 
\f0  Maintenance nightmare (3 parallel systems to validate)\
\
The hierarchical framing creates:\
- 
\f2 \uc0\u9989 
\f0  Clear default (Wisdom Voice)\
- 
\f2 \uc0\u9989 
\f0  Clear upgrade path (Relatable FP for Gen Z research)\
- 
\f2 \uc0\u9989 
\f0  Clear legacy handling (old mode deprecated but preserved)\
\
### **2. It Matches Your Actual Use Cases**\
\
Looking at your system:\
- **Most books**: Gen Z professionals, burnout, anxiety 
\f8 \uc0\u8594 
\f0  need safe, grounded voice\
- **Gen Z experiments**: Test relatable first-person based on research\
- **Legacy/compatibility**: Old books that used memoir opinion mode\
\
This is NOT "3 equal choices" - it's **stratified by risk and purpose**.\
\
### **3. It Protects Against Drift**\
\
Without hierarchy:\
- Developers might default to wrong mode\
- QA doesn't know which to test first\
- Users pick memoir mode "because it sounds interesting"\
\
With hierarchy:\
- **Default = safest** (Wisdom Voice)\
- **Advanced = intentional** (Relatable FP)\
- **Deprecated = visible warning** (Legacy Opinion)\
\
