\'93I always thought just being ready is the point,\'94 Idris Elba says in the new trailer for Kathryn Bigelow\'92s A HOUSE OF DYNAMITE. \'93It keeps people in check, keeps the world straight. If they see how prepared we are, no one starts a nuclear war.\'94 \
\
That isn\'92t how things turn out in A HOUSE OF DYNAMITE. As the trailer continues, we see an intercontinental ballistic missile heading for the United States, and a star-studded cast including Elba, Rebecca Ferguson, and Jason Clarke scrambling to respond. \'93These are dedicated professionals at the highest level of government being called on to make impossible decisions in the most extreme circumstances imaginable, which is almost scarier in a way,\'94 Bigelow tells Netflix. \
\
The new film from the Academy Award\'96winning director of The Hurt Locker is a global thriller with a meticulous attention to detail, bringing audiences into the halls of power as a nuclear crisis unfolds. \'93We invite the audience into the room,\'94 Bigelow said at a press conference following the film\'92s Venice Film Festival premiere. \'93And then, hopefully, it\'92s an invitation to decide what to do about all these weapons in a situation like this. What would we do? What would I do?\'94\
\
The film leaves the identity of the enemy ambiguous, instead focusing on the shock waves that rattle through the American government in response. \'93I wanted the view of the film to be trained inward, not outward, and for the audience to lean into the ambiguity at the heart of the nuclear debate: How can we call this defense when the outcome could well be total destruction?\'94 Bigelow says. \'93The antagonist is the system we\'92ve built to essentially end the world on a hair trigger.\'94\
\
